properties.Title: Update: Flood Warning Issued For The Red River At St. Jean Baptiste And St. Adolphe
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a Flood Warning on the Red River at St. Jean Baptiste and at St. Adolphe. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions given by local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-11-02T15:00:00-05:00

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Total snowfall: 15 to 35 cm. Locations: Upper Lake Melville, Eagle River, Rigolet, inland areas near Cartwright. Time span: continuing until late tonight. Remarks: Snow, heavy at times, will continue tonight. In the Upper Lake Melville area, 25 to 35 cm of snow is expected. For Rigolet, inland areas near Cartwright, and Eagle River, snowfall accumulations of 15 to 25 cm can be expected. The snow will mix with or change to rain along parts of the coast from Cartwright to Black Tickle. In the Eagle River area, the snow will change to ice pellets this evening. Additionally, northeasterly winds gusting to 50 or 60 km/h will give blowing snow over exposed areas tonight. The snow will taper to flurries by Saturday morning. ### Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-11-02T13:59:28-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-11-02T00:52:28-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2059495117.2019

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Maximum wind gusts: 80 km/h, except 100 along parts of the coast. Locations: over the Great Northern Peninsula. Time span: midnight tonight until Saturday morning. Remarks: Strong southwesterly winds will develop tonight with the highest gusts occurring during the overnight hours. Winds will begin to ease Saturday morning. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
